observations.recommendation:
We recommended that Management:
a. Require the Inventory Committee to:
a.1 Conduct a complete annual physical count of Property, Plant, and
Equipment (PPE);
a.2 Ensure that the required information in the Report on Physical Count
of Property, Plant, and Equipment (RPCPPE) is complete;
a.3 Comply with the submission of the RPCPPE on or before January 31 of
each year;
b. Direct the Municipal Accountant to:
b.1. Ensure that the road lot component of the local road networks is
properly accounted for and included in the financial reports;
b.2 Maintain the appropriate ledger cards for road networks following the
format in Annex D of COA Circular No. 2015-008 dated November 23,
2015;
b.3 Observe the proper disclosure of the road network systems in the Notes
to the Financial Statements in accordance with Annex B of the above-
mentioned Circular;
b.4 Update the property ledger cards to reflect the sufficient and particular
description of each PPE item;
c. Direct the Municipal Treasurer to:
c.1 Maintain an updated Local Road Inventory and Road Map;
c.2 Prepare the Report on Local Road Network as provided in Annex A of
the above-mentioned Circular;
c.2 Maintain a complete property card for each item of the PPE of the
LGU based on the physical count;
d. Require the Municipal Accountant and Municipal Treasurer of the
periodic reconciliation of property records;
e. Direct the Municipal Engineer to furnish the Municipal Accountant and
Municipal Treasurer with the complete description and cost segregation of
all road projects; and
f. Immediately order the conduct of the one-time cleansing of PPE accounts
under COA Circular No. 2020-006, to avoid continued and further
misstatement of these accounts in the ensuing years.

We recommended that Management:

direct the Inventory Committee to conduct the physical inventory taking of supplies and materials once every semester and prepare and submit the corresponding RPCI to the Audit Team within the set timeline;

require the concerned offices in-charge to submit the required documentations to record liquidation of Inventory Accounts;




direct the Municipal Accountant to prepare the necessary adjusting entries upon receipt of liquidation reports to reflect the true and correct balances; and maintain Stock Cards and Subsidiary Ledgers of each Inventory Accounts.

We recommended that Management direct the Municipal Accountant to:
reconcile the balances of Cash in Bank-LCCA account per books and per bank and effect the necessary adjustments;
prepare adjusting entries for all identified reconciling items in the books and for long outstanding and/or stale checks; Henceforth, record immediately the reconciling items after preparation of the BRS;
coordinate with the PVB to secure a copy of the loan agreement and the necessary documents needed in the booking up/recording of the Cash in Bank-LCSA; and
record appropriate entries to recognize the DSRA fund under the Cash in Bank – LCSA.

We recommended that Management:
allocate budget for the ₱12.97 million accrued payable for the terminal leave benefits earned by its employees;
include in the Annual Budget every year the appropriation for the accrued payable on terminal leave benefits earned by each employee per year to ensure that employee benefits are properly accounted for;
set-up a special fund for the accrued earned leave of employees to defray expenses of employees’ benefits in the future; and
direct the Municipal Accountant to make the necessary adjusting entries to record the accrued liability pertaining to the earned leave benefits of the employees after ensuring the correctness of the accumulated leave credit balances of employees as of December 31, 2020 and the budget was allocated for the same.

We recommended and Management agreed to:
submit the distribution lists of relief goods to forestall issuance of Notice of Suspension;
require the Municipal Accountant to record expenses charged to the Trust Liability- DRRM funds following the accounting entries as prescribed under COA Circular No. 2012-002;
require the supplier to submit valid official/collection receipts on procured items with expired receipts; and
ensure that the MDRRMFIP includes the activities to be funded from the unexpended QRF and DRRMF-MOOE of the previous years which were transferred to the Special Trust Fund.

We recommended that Management:
formulate a detailed systematic plan of activities per department. The planned activities shall integrate therewith the volume and frequency of regular and routine tasks to be performed to ensure that overtime services will be avoided;
consider the use of CTO as the remuneration for OT services rendered and justify that resort to OT pay fell under exceptional cases, if warranted;
require each employee to prepare only one DTR per month which includes both regular workday and overtime; and
direct the HRMO to formulate policy guidelines internal rules and procedures on the rendition of overtime services of their personnel and revisit the conditions on the authority to render overtime services under CSC-DBM Joint Circular No. 1 series of 2015.

We recommended that Management:

keep track and follow-up the review and approval of the LGU’s 10-year Solid Waste Management Plan and immediately submit a copy of the 10-year Solid Waste Management Plan to the Office of the Auditor upon receipt thereof;

require MENRO in coordination with the Municipal Management Board to provide a concrete plan for the operation of the MRF and provide an appropriate alternative plan on proper waste disposal while still in the process of waiting approval of the 10-year Solid Waste Management Plan/Program by the DENR;

require the Municipal Management Board to strategically plan to ensure implementation and enforcement of the provisions of the Act; and

require the MENRO in coordination with the Municipal Management Board to the respond to the matter and ensure that the 10-year Solid Waste Management Plan/Program for the safe and sanitary management of the solid waste generation is consistent with the national framework and in accordance with the Act and of the policies set by the National Solid Waste Management Commission.

We recommended that Management:

ensure that only those conventions, trainings and seminars which are highly relevant, mandatory and responsive to the capacity-building needs or requirements of the LGU are attended and participated in by the most qualified people in the LGU to avoid any wasteful and inefficient utilization of fund;

conduct prior assessment or evaluation of participants’ qualifications, training needs, and available resources; 

to submit the following: 1) proof that Provoya Travel and Tours is an accredited training provider; 2) approved Itinerary of Travel, both appendix A and B, by each participant; 3) justification on the need and qualification of each participant to attend said seminars outside Bicol Region; and

to submit copy of 2017 Capability Development Agenda of the Municipality. Non-submission of these documents shall warrant the issuance of Notice of Suspension/Disallowance.

